 tie breath to the transcendent and the natural, Heine traces a decoupling of breath from its traditional association with life, and asks what literature might lie beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterary style. 0aRespiration in literature. 0aRespiration. 0aRhythm in literature. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : Poetry. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848359740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438483597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438483597/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles